Requirement

R package pathifier Use the R package pathifier to calculate the pathway score of a specified gene based on the gene expression levels of the sample and draw a heatmap.

https://www.thno.org/v08p6386.htm From https://www.thno.org/v08p6386.htm

Figure 4. Identification of non-luminal-like subgroup from ER+PR-HER2- breast cancer. (B) Enriched pathways in the Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) collection of the non-luminal-like subgroup compared to the luminal-like subgroup of the TCGA cohort by Pathifier algorithm. Heatmap showing the pathway scores of each ER+PR-HER2- tumor.

The non-luminal-like subtype in the ER+PR-HER2- group presented higher Pathifier [29] scores in biosynthesis, metabolism and DNA replication (Figure 4B) and lower endocrine sensitivity scores (P<0.05, Figure 4C and Figure S7A).

Application Scenarios

GSEA When performing enrichment analysis or GSEA using a differentially expressed gene list, pathways of interest may not be visible due to parameter settings. In such cases, converting the gene expression matrix to a pathway expression matrix allows direct visualization of the pathway of interest.

RGSVAFigureYa61GSVA Alternatively, the R package GSVA can also perform similar functions. For usage, see FigureYa61GSVA.

cogena Custom function (from cogena)

# gmtpathifier
# Read the gmt file as a list to meet the pathifier input requirements
gmt2list <- function(annofile){
  if (!file.exists(annofile)) {
    stop("There is no such gmt file.")
  }
  
  if (tools::file_ext(annofile) == "xz") {
    annofile <- xzfile(annofile)
    x <- scan(annofile, what="", sep="\n", quiet=TRUE)
    close(annofile)
  } else if (tools::file_ext(annofile) == "gmt") {
    x <- scan(annofile, what="", sep="\n", quiet=TRUE)
  } else {
    stop ("Only gmt and gmt.xz are accepted for gmt2list")
  }
  
  y <- strsplit(x, "\t")
  names(y) <- sapply(y, `[[`, 1)
  
  annoList <- lapply(y, `[`, c(-1,-2))
}

genelist

Genelist of pathways of interest

pathifiergmt/ When running pathifier, the more pathways/genes in the gmt file, the longer it takes.

gmt How can I obtain the gmt file for the pathway of interest?

  • GSEAgmthttp://software.broadinstitute.org/gsea/downloads.jsp
  • gmt
  • https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/O1xd5l5h33fXUWOvX3UBGwTermTermgenelistFigureYa136fgsea
  • Method 1: Download the gmt file from the GSEA website http://software.broadinstitute.org/gsea/downloads.jsp and use it directly (this process may take a long time).
  • Method 2: Extract the pathway of interest from the gmt file obtained in Method 1.
  • Method 3: Use differentially expressed genes from published articles. For ideas, refer to this article: https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/O1xd5l5h33fXUWOvX3UBGw: If Im truly interested in and obsessed with a concept or term, Ill find articles that publish related functions or pathways and rebuild the terms genelist. For similar ideas, refer to Figure Ya136fgsea.

gene_paper*.txt Save the gene names of interest to a text file, one gene per line, one column, named gene_paper*.txt

read.aschar <- function(filename){
  file <- read.table(filename)
  file <- file$V1
}

Input files

easy_input_expr.txt easy_input_expr.txt, gene expression matrix.

easy_input_info.txt easy_input_info.txt, sample information.

## 
## Expression matrix
expr <- read.table("easy_input_expr.txt",sep = "\t",check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T,row.names = 1)
expr[1:3, 1:3]
##        BRCA-A06N-01A BRCA-A07S-01A BRCA-A084-01A
## TSPAN6         13.71         10.99          3.10
## TNMD            0.00          0.08          0.00
## DPM1           33.86         22.80         31.14
# 
# Remove lowly expressed genes
expr <- expr[rowSums(expr) > 1,]

## pathway score
## Extract tumor and normal samples for pathway score calculation
sinfo <- read.table("easy_input_info.txt",sep = "\t",check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T,row.names = 1)
head(sinfo)
##               er_status_by_ihc pr_status_by_ihc HER2.KH.FISH2.0
## BRCA-A3IZ-01A         Positive         Negative        Negative
## BRCA-A66N-01A         Positive         Negative        Negative
## BRCA-A13E-01A         Positive         Negative        Negative
## BRCA-A0J5-01A         Positive         Negative        Negative
## BRCA-A0SW-01A         Positive         Negative        Negative
## BRCA-A107-01A         Positive         Negative        Negative
##                          PAM50
## BRCA-A3IZ-01A     Luminal-like
## BRCA-A66N-01A     Luminal-like
## BRCA-A13E-01A Non-luminal-like
## BRCA-A0J5-01A     Luminal-like
## BRCA-A0SW-01A     Luminal-like
## BRCA-A107-01A     Luminal-like
tum.sam <- intersect(colnames(expr)[grep("-01A",colnames(expr))],rownames(sinfo)) # ER+PR-HER2- # Extract primary tumors that meet the requirements (in this example, ER+PR-HER2-).
nor.sam <- colnames(expr)[grep("-11A",colnames(expr))] #  # Extract adjacent tissue

expr <- expr[,c(tum.sam,nor.sam)] #  # Reorder
tissue.logic <- rep(c(F,T),c(length(tum.sam),length(nor.sam))) #  # Construct an indicator variable for whether the sample is normal

## luminal-likeNon-luminal-like 
## Divide into two groups based on luminal-like and non-luminal-like patterns. This grouping will be used when plotting.
# luminal-like samples
lum.sam <- intersect(rownames(sinfo[which(sinfo$PAM50 == "Luminal-like"),]),tum.sam)
# Non-luminal-like samples
nonlum.sam <- intersect(rownames(sinfo[which(sinfo$PAM50 == "Non-luminal-like"),]),tum.sam)

pathifier

Run pathifier

pathway score Calculate pathway scores using tumor and adjacent adjacent regions.

gmtGSEA>1000 Note: This uses a manually corrected gmt file. If using GSEA pathways (>1000), the algorithm will run very slowly.

GSEAc510 A rough estimate is that running the c5 immune-related pathway in GSEA may take over 10 days.

indata <- as.matrix(log2(expr + 1))
gname <- rownames(expr)
path.res <- quantify_pathways_deregulation(data = indata, # () # Expression profiles, behavioral genes, listed as samples (must be a matrix)
                                           allgenes = gname, #  # Gene names for the expression profiles
                                           syms = gset, #  # List of pathways of interest
                                           pathwaynames = names(gset), #   # Pathway names for the pathway list
                                           normals = tissue.logic, # TRUE # Indicator variable, TRUE if the value is adjacent to the cancer
                                           attempts = 100, # 100 # Number of runs, defaults to 100; increasing the number may improve stability
                                           min_exp = 0, # 4 # Default is 4. If the expression value is below this threshold, the threshold is padded.
                                           min_std = 0) # 0.4 # Default is 0.4. If the standard deviation of a gene is below this threshold, the normalization is divided by the threshold instead of the true standard deviation.

Next, plot a heatmap of the pathway of interest.

scoreFigureYa61GSVA You can also calculate the scores for all pathways and perform differential expression analysis. The method is similar to gene differential expression analysis, see Figure Ya61 GSVA.

Start plotting

Here, we replicate the original method, without clustering.

FigureYa91cluster_heatmap For more clustering and ranking heatmap plotting techniques, see Figure Ya91 cluster_heatmap.

#  Here, we use colors to plot sample information in the figure.
# illustratorpdf # You can also open the PDF file in Illustrator and add horizontal lines as in the example.
annCol <- data.frame(PAM50 = sinfo$PAM50,row.names = rownames(sinfo),stringsAsFactors = F)
annColors <- list("PAM50" = c("Luminal-like" = "red","Non-luminal-like" = "blue"))

# 
# Normalize the heatmap data
plotdata <- t(scale(t(path.score[,c(nonlum.sam,lum.sam)])))
plotdata[plotdata > 1]  <- 1 # 11 # Values greater than 1 are assigned a value of 1.
plotdata[plotdata < -1] <- -1 # -1-1 # Values less than -1 are assigned a value of -1.

#pdf("pathifier.pdf",width = 15,height = 3)
pheatmap(plotdata,
         border_color = NA, # #no border
         cluster_cols = F, cluster_rows = F, #  #no clustering
         #color = greenred(64), # #original red and green color scheme
         annotation_col = annCol[c(nonlum.sam,lum.sam),,drop = F], # #sample information
         annotation_colors = annColors, # #sample information color scheme
         show_rownames = T, # #show pathway names
         show_colnames = F) # #do not show sample names
